Description Of Each Command Switch
**********************************

Astrolog allows command line switches to be invoked with either the
leading dash (@{b}-@{ub}) standard to Unix users, or a leading slash (@{b}/@{ub}) that PC
users are more accustomed to. Not only that, but the leading character
is actually optional. For example, the command

     @{b}astrolog -i chartfile -R -u -U -Z -Xs 300 -Xi -XB@{ub}

can be done as

     @{b}astrolog /i chartfile /r /u /U /Z /Xs 300@{ub},

or can be abbreviated as just

     @{b}astrolog i chartfile R u U Z Xs 300 Xi XB@{ub}.

(This is subject to a couple of minor limitations, in that one can't
have the @{b}-1@{ub} or @{b}-3@{ub} option follow a @{b}-R@{ub} restriction list of numbers, since
the @{b}-1@{ub} will be considered a number.)

Many switches in their standard form are technically a `toggle' instead
of a `set' for the particular feature in question.  For example,
@{b}astrolog -v -g -g@{ub} will only result in the @{b}-v@{ub} chart being printed; an
aspect grid won't, because the first @{b}-g@{ub} turned it on while the second
@{b}-g@{ub} turned it off again.  This can be useful, in say the @{b}-e@{ub}
everything switch.  If you want all of Astrolog's charts except the
astro-graph, you can do @{b}astrolog -e -L@{ub}, where the @{b}-e@{ub} turns everything
on and the @{b}-L@{ub} turns the astro-graph chart, already on because of @{b}-e@{ub},
off.  In another example, to get a chart with only the stars in it, one
can do @{b}astrolog -R0 -RU@{ub}, where the @{b}-R0@{ub} restricts everything, and the
@{b}-RU@{ub} unrestricts all the stars.  The various @{b}-X@{ub} switches which set a
mode in graphics are also toggles - a combination like @{b}-Xr -Xr@{ub} which
with one instance will just go into reverse video mode, will remain out
of it because the first @{b}-Xr@{ub} put you in and the second toggled you back
out.

Command switch flags may actually be forced on or off regardless of
their current setting with special character prefixes.  Many switches
(such as @{b}-s@{ub}) represent on/off flags and their setting is toggled when
the switch is encountered.  However this alone doesn't allow one to
force the setting to be a value, as we don't know if it needs to be
toggled or not.  Prefixing any flag switch with @{b}_@{ub} will reset its state
even if already off, while prefixing with @{b}=@{ub} will always make it on.
For example, putting @{b}_s@{ub} on a command line will always set tropical
zodiac, while @{b}=s@{ub} will always set sidereal.  The standard @{b}-@{ub} and @{b}/@{ub}
prefixes, along with no prefix at all, always toggle the current
setting.  This is useful for configuration files where we want to set
various flags to particular values.  There's one more obscure switch
prefix which is @{b}:@{ub}, which doesn't affect the setting at all, but still
affects any subsetting parameters.  For example, @{b}:I 80@{ub} won't affect the
interpretation setting at all, but will still set the default screen width
to 80 columns.  This is slightly simpler than the @{b}-I 80 -I@{ub} double
toggle hack that would have to be done to do such a thing otherwise.

The various static help listings that may be generated, such as the
lists from @{b}-H@{ub}, @{b}-HO@{ub}, @{b}-HI@{ub}, and so on, may be combined with each other and
even the actual charts. For convenience the program will terminate
right away and not prompt for chart info if the only thing specified is
one of the tables, e.g. just @{b}-H@{ub} will print the help list and exit, but
@{b}-H -i file -g@{ub} will print the help list followed by an aspect grid chart.

In the command list below, greater than/less than symbols (@{b}<@{ub} and @{b}>@{ub}) are
used to denote a command switch parameter to be replaced by the
appropriate value, brackets (@{b}[@{ub} and @{b}]@{ub}) are used to denote an optional
parameter, and commas are used to separate either/or choices. For
example, the specification of the @{b}-I@{ub} switch is @{b}-I [<columns>]@{ub}, meaning
that one can specify the @{b}-I@{ub} switch, followed a parameter for the number
of screen columns, but that this extra parameter is optional. The
specification of the @{b}-Xs@{ub} switch is @{b}-Xs <100,200,300,400>@{ub}, meaning it
can be used as either @{b}-Xs 100@{ub}, @{b}-Xs 200@{ub}, @{b}-Xs 300@{ub}, or @{b}-Xs 400@{ub}.  An
ellipsis (@{b}..@{ub}) generally refers to a variable length list of values or
an abbreviation for something already indicated in related switches.

Correct parsing of strings is done on the command line (and in files
since they are technically command lines) in addition to when the user
is being prompted for data within the program.  For example, to do the
natal chart for the @{b}alt.astrology@{ub} newsgroup using the @{b}-qa@{ub} switch, one
may enter the intuitive

     @{b}-qa Jul 29 1991ad 6:23pm -10 151e13 33s52@{ub}.

The items may be entered in other standard and simpler forms as well,
such as just

     @{b}-qa 7 29 1991 18.23 -10 -151.13 -33.52@{ub}.

Any command switch that takes an index number as a parameter may have
it specified by its actual name instead of a hard to remember value.
For example, the switch sequence @{b}-c 1 -R 6 -A 5 -F 7 10 0@{ub} may also be
entered as the more understandable @{b}-c Koch -R Jupiter -A Sextile -F
Saturn Capricorn 0@{ub}.  Any string may be abbreviated to its first three
characters.  Aspects should be based on their formal abbreviations,
e.g. @{b}ssx@{ub} instead of @{b}sem@{ub} for Semisextile.  (Presently only the first
three characters are ever looked at, so some star objects may still
need to be specified as a number since they have the same first three
letters.)


